'''Anatoly Georgiyevich Bokschanin''' (28 March 1903, [[Moscow]] – 24 January 1979, Moscow) was a [[Soviet]] scholar of [[classical antiquity]]. He was a [[Doktor nauk|Doctor of Sciences]] and Professor of the [[Moscow University]].<ref name="aar">{{cite web | url =http://antiquites.academic.ru/355/%D0%91%D0%BE%D0%BA%D1%89%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%BD,_%D0%90%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%B9_%D0%93%D0%B5%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%B5%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%87| script-title=ru:Бокщанин, Анатолий Георгиевич |language=Russian|publisher =Antiquites.academic.ru| accessdate =23 Aug 2014}}</ref>
Bokschanin researched the political history of the [[Roman Empire]] of the 1st century AD and [[Roman–Persian relations|Roman–Parthian relations]].<ref name="aar"/> He penned several scholar publications and authored and edited several textbooks on [[Roman history]].<ref name="aar"/> His major works include "Иудейские восстания II в. н.э." ("Judean Revolts of the 2nd century AD", 1950), "Социальный кризис Римской империи в I в. н.э." ("Social Crisis of the Roman Empire in the 1st century AD", 1954), ''Парфия и Рим'' (''Parthia and Rome'', in two parts, 1960) and "Источниковедение Древнего Рима" ("The Source Studies of Ancient Rome", 1981). Two articles about Bokschanin appeared in the Russian ''[[Journal of Ancient History]]'' (1973, issue 4, p.&nbsp;198 and 1979, issue 4).
