'''Heinrich Kretschmayr''' (1870&ndash;1939) was Austrian archivist and historian<ref>{{cite book|title=A Companion to Venetian History, 1400-1797|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2ascAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA13|date=11 July 2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-25252-3|page=13|quote=...Austrian archivist and historian Heinrich Kretschmayr.}}</ref> who specialized in the history of [[Venetian Republic|Venice]].<ref name="Madden2008">{{cite book|author=Thomas F. Madden|title=Enrico Dandolo and the Rise of Venice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sk9lvXUMHpYC&pg=PA31|accessdate=7 June 2013|date=1 April 2008|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-0-8018-9184-7|page=31|quote=the great historian of Venice Heinrich Kretschmayr}}</ref>

The first volume of Kretschmayr's work "The History of Venice" as "''Geschichte von Venedig''"  was published in 1905, the second was interrupted by the outbreak of the [[World War I|First World War]] and did not appear until 1920, and for the destruction of his notes in a 1927 fire, the third not until 1933. Attempts to publish an Italian translation were equally star-crossed: both Kretschmayr and his Italian translator died in 1939, the project was put on hold during the [[World War II|Second World War]], then completed in the post-war years, but inexplicably never published. His work outgrew the 19th century tradition in historiography.<ref>{{cite book|title=A Companion to Venetian History, 1400-1797|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2ascAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA13|date=11 July 2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-25252-3|page=13}}</ref> 

