'''Jacqueline Netter-Minne-Guerroudj''' (1919 &ndash; 18 January 2015) was a Frenchwoman condemned to death as an accomplice of 
[[Fernand Yveton|Fernand Iveton]] during the [[Algerian War]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Décès de la moudjahida Jacqueline Guerroudj| url=http://www.aps.dz/algerie/16602-d%C3%A9c%C3%A8s-de-la-moudjahida-jacqueline-guerroudj|agency=Algerie Presse Service|date=19 January 2015|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611172449/http://www.aps.dz/algerie/16602-d%C3%A9c%C3%A8s-de-la-moudjahida-jacqueline-guerroudj|archive-date=2015-06-11}}</ref> She was never executed, partly due to a campaign on her behalf conducted by [[Simone de Beauvoir]].{{sfn|Tidd|1999|p=111}}

She was born to a bourgeois family in [[Rouen]] in 1919. She arrived in Algeria in 1948 as the wife of Pierre Minne, a professor of Philosophy.{{sfn|Dore-Audibert|1995|p=142}} She remarried in 1950 to [[Abdelkader Guerroudj]] (nicknamed "Djilali"), an activist in the FLN. On December 4, 1957, Guerroudj's daughter by her first marriage, [[Danièle Djamila Amrane-Minne|Danièle Minne]], was sentenced to 7 years in prison by a tribunal for juveniles.{{sfn|Dore-Audibert|1995|p=146}} Guerroudj died on 18 January 2015 in [[Algiers]], Algeria.

